  ('partner-reactive-medicine-ball-toss-and-relocate', 'Throwing is a linked kinetic-chain skill. Partner Reactive Medicine Ball Toss and Relocate targets a piece of that chain so the athlete can create force, transfer force, decelerate, or maintain joint position without relying only on the arm.', 'Belongs in Movement Intelligence because the athlete must perceive, coordinate, relocate, and reset with quality before speed or fatigue becomes the main stressor.', 'Use on throwing or lifting days only when it supports the main goal. Keep high-intent work early and fresh; place strength after skill/output unless it is the primary training block; use resilience work after main throwing or in lower-intensity support sessions.', 'Do not add speed, choice, or partner pressure before the athlete can solve the base task. Stop when decisions, spacing, timing, or posture degrade.', 'Regress range, load, speed, distance, partner pressure, cue complexity, or total reps before removing quality. Progress only after the athlete owns pain-free mechanics and recovery between reps.'),
  ('throwing-athlete-trap-bar-deadlift', 'Throwing is a linked kinetic-chain skill. Trap Bar Deadlift targets a piece of that chain so the athlete can create force, transfer force, decelerate, or maintain joint position without relying only on the arm.', 'Belongs in Capacity because the primary adaptation is force production, local strength, or loaded robustness rather than max-speed throwing skill.', 'Use on throwing or lifting days only when it supports the main goal. Keep high-intent work early and fresh; place strength after skill/output unless it is the primary training block; use resilience work after main throwing or in lower-intensity support sessions.', 'Do not place heavy strength work immediately before high-skill throwing if it changes mechanics. Progress load only while range, posture, and rep speed stay controlled.', 'Regress range, load, speed, distance, partner pressure, cue complexity, or total reps before removing quality. Progress only after the athlete owns pain-free mechanics and recovery between reps.'),
